g to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Atholl","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish, English:  see  Athol  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Athol","meanings":["Scottish: A male name derived from Athol, in Scotland."]}]},{"name":"Duncan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Donnchadh , also used among people without Scottish connections. This was the name of a 7th-century Scottish saint (abbot of Iona) and two medieval kings of Scotland. The final ‐<i>n</i> in the Anglicized form seems to be the result of confusion with the Gaelic word <i>ceann</i> ‘head’ in the Latinized form <i>Duncanus</i>.  Compare Irish  Donagh ."],"variants":[{"name":"Donnchadh","meanings":["Gaelic: compound of Old Celtic <i>donn</i> ‘brown’ + <i>chadh</i> ‘chief’ or ‘noble’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Duncan Mormaer Of Atholl was born in 0949, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Duncan Macduncan Thane Of Dule Abbot Of Dunkeld, was 29 and his mother, Conall Dun Caillen, was 29. He had at least 1 son with Althelreda of Dunbar. In 994, his occupation is listed as hereditary priest & abthane of dull. He died in 0990, in Scotland, at the age of 41, and was buried in Iona, Argyll and Bute, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"0949–990":"0949–0990","0949–0990":"0949–0990","0950–1010":"0950